entry.title: [balance-text] Fix break token propagation
entry.content:
When crrev.com/c/4369820 tried to move `PropagatedBreakTokens`

out of `NGLineBreaker`, it did:

1. Move propagated break tokens while line breaking to

`NGLineInfo`.

2. Move propagated break tokens while `CreateLine` to

`NGInlineChildLayoutContext`.



2 was not correct, because the algorithm may retry not only

line breaking but also `CreateLine` in certain cases, and

propagated break tokens from non-final `CreateLine` should not

be added to `NGInlineChildLayoutContext`.



This patch fixes this by changing `CreateLine` to add

propagated break tokens to `NGLineInfo`, and move them to

`NGInlineChildLayoutContext` only if the line layout is final.

entry.title: Introduce WarmUpServiceWorker
entry.content:
This CL introduces WarmUpServiceWorker function which warms-up Service

Workers. WarmUpServiceWorker prepares the renderer process, initializes

mojo pipes, and loads top-level scripts without evaluating the Service

Worker's top-level script.



[How warmed-up Service Worker behaves]



After the service worker is warmed-up, the running_status() will be kept

as `STARTING` status.



There are the following scenarios after Service Worker is warmed-up.



A) Time out (after kWarmUpDuration) => Service Worker will stop.

B) Be requested to warm-up again => Extend the time out.

C) Be requested to start => Call `InitializeGlobalScope`.



[How WarmUpServiceWorker works]



WarmUpServiceWorker postpones initializing the global scope. This is

controlled by pause_initializing_global_scope_ flag and

SetPauseInitializingGlobalScope() and ResumeInitializingGlobalScope()

functions.



The following trace logs demonstrate how WarmUpServiceWorker behaves.





https://ui.perfetto.dev/#!/?s=360cc921e9f9563a26de4e7a627bc9fe8ce3bdccf7798f4d372ba71581b16313





https://ui.perfetto.dev/#!/?s=76d3599d825e37c66797380c2696f34d9166e513e998d59d47c4cd99314cb55a



[History of InitializeGlobalScope (delayed global scope initialization)]



In the past, ServiceWorker::InitializeGlobalScope mojo API was used to

prevent from evaluating a script until the byte-for-byte comparison or

COEP check is completed (https://crrev.com/c/2060446). However, this is

not needed after off-the-main-thread service worker script

fetch. PlzServiceWorker CL (https://crrev.com/c/3382976) also cleaned up

the delayed global scope initialization code. Now this CL utilizes the

delayed global scope initialization mechanism to implement

WarmUpServiceWorker.

entry.title: arc: Add ArcExternalStorageAccess feature
entry.content:
The feature allows developers to control access to external storage

devices (e.g. USB flash drives, SD cards) by Android apps. It is enabled

by default, and when it's disabled, mounting events of external storage

devices are blocked by ArcVolumeMounterBridge and not propagated to ARC.



Note that unmounting events are no-op but still propagated to ARC just

to make the behavior aligned with the ExternalStorageDisabled policy;

the policy can be changed runtime and thus it's reasonable to propagate

unmounting events to ARC to make sure things are properly cleaned up.



At the moment, the feature lacks proper UI integration. For example,

even when it's disabled, external drives will still be displayed in the

Files app when opened by Android apps, Android apps will be suggested

when the user tries to open a file in an external drive from the Files

app, etc. However, it should be acceptable for a feature behind a flag.



Bug: b:278960672

Test: Toggle the feature and confirm that removable media volumes are

Test: mounted on the ARC side iff the feature is enabled.

entry.title: [GPU] Add feature to crash on context loss when running ANGLE in-process
entry.content:
When the GPU service is running in the host process, it does not exit

on context loss even when it otherwise would. However, context loss when

Chrome/WebView are running with WebView is currently not recoverable:

there would need to be a termination and re-initialization of GL, which

Chrome doesn't do. This means that such a context loss will almost

certainly result in a loop of re-initializing and losing contexts,

causing undefined behavior and a likely eventual browser crash.



This CL adds functionality to have the GPU service immediately crash

when running in-process with ANGLE if asked to restart due to a backend

context loss (note that we *don't* do this on synthetic context loss

events generated by Chrome, as these *are* recoverable). We will monitor

the impact on crash rate to determine if we need to invest in making

context loss recoverable in this situation (it won't necessarily have a

significant impact on crash rate: as we noted above, this flow is likely

already resulting in eventual app crashes).



The new behavior is gated by a disabled-by-default Finch flag, so this

CL will not in of itself change any behavior.



Bug: 1432913

entry.title: [compile hints] Fix deps around blink core
entry.content:
The buildflag header added recently in blink/renderer/bindings takes

part in some less obvious parts of the build, deps-wise, and made it

so several compiles could flake in a clean build, such as:

obj/third_party/blink/renderer/core/core_hot/document.o

obj/third_party/blink/renderer/core/animation/animation/animation_timeline.o

obj/third_party/blink/renderer/core/exported/exported/web_document.o

(and more from core/core_hot, core/animation, core/exported).



In the core_hot example, the error looks like this:

In file included from ../../third_party/blink/renderer/core/dom/document.cc:129:

In file included from ../../third_party/blink/renderer/core/dom/context_features.h:32:

In file included from ../../third_party/blink/renderer/core/page/page.h:44:

../../third_party/blink/renderer/bindings/core/v8/v8_compile_hints.h:8:10:

fatal error: 'third_party/blink/renderer/bindings/buildflags.h' file not found



Fix by (1) adding the dep in core_generated, which most relevant targets

already depend on, and (2) adding the dep separately in core_hot,

because that doesn't use core_generated and I'm not sure if it should,

since it already reproduces other necessary deps directly.

entry.title: media/gpu/VP8VaapiVED: Specify a loop filter level by rate controller

Originally, we set the highest loop filter level, 63, all the time. It

causes inefficiency in compression; an encoder driver produces the

large chunk even for identical frames. We need to rather specify a

smaller loop filter level [1].
